Work in Japan included considerable disc machine work to reproduce the phenomenon e.g. [18] and confirmation of the desirability of grinding rails to control development of RCF defects in general, and squats in particular [10]. Monitoring undertaken on Shinkansen lines gave a rough idea of the rates at which squats developed (Fig. 4) and showed that a few tens of MGT of traffic were required to initiate the seeds of a squat. Grinding is best undertaken at that time to arrest squat development. About 100 MGT of traffic was required for a crack to develop to the edge of the layer of compressive residual stress that exists below the running surface of the rail. This life is broadly consistent with experience on railways elsewhere:


‘it is unusual for squats to be evident in rails less than 10 years old or those that have carried less than 150 EMGT of traffic’ [1] (an EMGT or equivalent million gross tonnes is a measure developed in the UK to try to account for damage that is not proportional to static load e.g. dynamic effects due to unsprung mass);

the youngest rail in which squats had been found in the UK (on a line carrying no more than 20 MGT per annum) was 7 years old [14];

on the ‘worst affected track the rail life has been reduced to about 15 years’ [14];

squats on the SNCF conventional network reduce rail life by about 150 MGT [19];

